CARVE-OUT FOR PRIMARY LEGAL SOURCES (added 2026-05-11):

The Atlas legal corpus (under `src/data/legal-sources/` and `src/data/legal-cases/`)
references and may quote underlying primary legal sources — statutes,
regulations, court decisions and treaty texts — that are themselves outside
the scope of this proprietary licence and instead governed by the relevant
jurisdiction's public-domain or open-government regime. Examples include:

  - § 5 Abs. 1 UrhG (DE) — Gesetze, Verordnungen, amtliche Erlasse,
    amtlich verfasste Leitsätze sind gemeinfrei.
  - Commission Decision 2011/833/EU (EU) — Eur-Lex content reuse with
    attribution.
  - 17 USC § 105 (US) — Works of the U.S. Government are not subject to
    copyright.
  - Open Government Licence v3.0 (UK) — Crown copyright works.
  - CPI Art. L122-5 2° (FR) — French statutes outside copyright monopoly.
  - UN Treaty Series — public-domain via UN Secretariat.

Caelex does NOT claim copyright in the underlying primary statutory text,
court decision text, or treaty text where the source jurisdiction's regime
places those materials outside private copyright. Caelex DOES claim
copyright in the editorial layer over those materials (paraphrase,
selection, taxonomy, cross-references, translations, annotations).

For the per-jurisdiction list and the operational rules see
`src/data/LEGAL-SOURCES-README.md`.

